(44, 'Suresh Gopi', 'http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b6/Suresh_Gopi.jpg/220px-Suresh_Gopi.jpg', 1, 'Suresh Gopinathan Nair (born 26 June 1959),[1] often credited as Suresh Gopi (Malayalam: à´¸àµà´°àµ‡à´·àµ à´—àµ‹à´ªà´¿), is a national award winning Indian film actor who works mainly in Malayalam cinema; he is famous for his roles in police dramas. He is noted for his leading roles as much as his character roles. He is also famous for his philanthropic efforts.[4]', 0),
(45, 'Mammootty', 'http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0a/Mammootty_malayalam.jpg', 1, 'Mammootty (born Muhammadkutty Ismail Panaparambil on 7 September 1951[1][3]) is an Indian film actor and producer who works mainly in Malayalam cinema. He has also acted in a few Tamil, Hindi, Telugu, and Kannada films. During a career spanning more than three decades, he has acted in more than 360 films,[4] and is only next to Prem Nazir in the number of lead roles in Indian films. He also appeared in the highest number of dual roles (nine) in Malayalam films.[5]', 0),
(46, 'Kanika', 'http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/17/Kanihaa.jpg/220px-Kanihaa.jpg', 1, 'Divya Venkatasubramaniam (Tamil: à®¤à®¿à®µà¯à®¯à®¾ à®µà¯†à®™à¯à®•à®Ÿà®šà¯à®ªà¯à®°à®®à®£à®¿à®¯à®®à¯; born 3 July 1982), best known by her stage name Kanika (also spelled Kaniha),[1][2] is an Indian film actress, occasional dubbing artist, playback singer, and TV anchor. Making her debut in the 2002 Tamil film Five Star, she went on to work in other South Indian film industries, including Telugu, Malayalam and Kannada, as well. She is perhaps best known for her performances as Eashwari in her debut film Five Star, Gayathri in Varalaru - History of Godfather and Thenmozhi in Autograph. She m', 0),
(47, 'Nedumudi Venu', 'http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9b/Nedumudi_Venu_2008.jpg/220px-Nedumudi_Venu_2008.jpg', 1, 'K. Venu Gopal (born 22 May 1948), known popularly by his stage name Nedumudi Venu (Malayalam: à´¨àµ†à´Ÿàµà´®àµà´Ÿà´¿ à´µàµ‡à´£àµ), is a Malayalam film actor from Kerala, India. He has also written screenplays and has directed one film.[1][2][3][4]', 0),
(48, 'Biju Menon', 'http://bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.20wmf3/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4', 1, 'Biju Menon is an Indian film actor who has mainly worked in Malayalam cinema, along with a couple of Tamil and Telugu films. He appears mostly in supporting roles, but has also acted in antagonistic roles. He made his debut in 1995 in Puthran.', 0),
(49, 'Saikumar (Malayalam actor)', 'http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d1/InterlanguageLinks-Asset-Pencil-Hover.gif', 1, 'Saikumar is a popular Malayalam actor. He is known for his handling of serious roles, though he started his career with comedy roles. Of late, he has been doing many negative roles as well.', 0),
(50, 'Dileep (actor)', 'http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b5/Dileep_2008.jpg/220px-Dileep_2008.jpg', 1, 'Dileep (Malayalam: à´¦à´¿à´²àµ€à´ªàµ; born Gopalakrishnan Padmanabhan Pillai on 27 October 1968) is an Indian film actor, mimicry artist and producer best known for his work in Malayalam cinema.', 0),
(51, 'Jagathy Sreekumar', 'http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/Jagathy_Sreekumar_2008.jpg/220px-Jagathy_Sreekumar_2008.jpg', 1, 'Sreekumar Achary, better known by his stage name Jagathy Sreekumar, is an Indian film actor who has performed in more than 1,000 Malayalam films.[1] He has also directed two films and has written screenplays for two films. His stage name is derived from the neighbourhood of Jagathy in Thiruvananthapuram, from where he hails.', 0),
(52, 'Vijayaraghavan (actor)', 'http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ef/Vijayaraghavan.jpg/220px-Vijayaraghavan.jpg', 1, 'Vijayaraghavan (Malayalam: à´µà´¿à´œà´¯à´°à´¾à´˜à´µàµ») is an Indian actor who mainly acts in Malayalam cinema. He is popular for his character roles. He is the son of popular drama and cinema artist N. N. Pillai.', 0),
(53, 'Samyuktha Varma', 'http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png', 1, 'Samyuktha Varma ( à´¸à´‚à´¯àµà´•àµà´¤ à´µàµ¼à´®àµà´® ), born November 26, 1982[1] is an award winning actress in Malayalam Movie Industry. She entered filmdom through the Malayalam movie Veendum Chila Veettukaryangal directed by Sathyan Anthikkad. Then she acted in several Malayalam feature films and bagged some awards. Later she left the scene after her marriage to actor Biju Menon.[2]', 0),
(54, 'Revathi', 'http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/Revathi_at_the_screening_of_Masaala_at_PVR_Phoenix_%281%29_%28cropped%29.jpg/220px-Revathi_at_the_screening_of_Masaala_at_PVR_Phoenix_%281%29_%28cropped%29.jpg', 1, 'Revathy (born as Asha Kelunni Kutty on 8 July 1966) is an Indian actress and film director. She has acted in Tamil, Malayalam, Kannada, Telugu and Hindi films, directed several feature-length films, and has acted in and produced multiple television programs, totaling over twenty years of experience in the entertainment industry and over a hundred films to her credit. She has won several accolades, including three National Film Awards, in three different categories, and six Filmfare Awards South.', 0),
(55, 'Vasundhara Das', 'http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/Vasundhara_das.jpg/220px-Vasundhara_das.jpg', 1, 'Vasundhara Das (born 1977), is an Indian singer and actress. She has acted in Hindi, Tamil, Kannada and Malayalam films. She is the co-founder of world music band Arya. As a playback singer, she is best remembered for singing "Shakalaka Baby" from the Tamil film Mudhalvan, which was also her debut song. She has performed many hit songs in Hindi and Tamil films thereafter.', 0),
(56, 'Devayani (actress)', 'http://bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.20wmf3/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4', 1, 'Devayani (born Sushma Jayadev on 22 June 1973) is an Indian film actress. She starred in numerous Tamil, Telugu and Malayalam films, along with a few Hindi films and one Bengali film. She received the Tamil Nadu State Film Awards for her performances in the films Kadhal Kottai and Surya Vamsam.[1][2] She has also appeared in the films Bharathi, Friends and Azhagi as well as in the Sun TV series Kolangal.', 0),
(57, 'Mukesh (actor)', 'http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/05/Mukesh_malayalam.jpg/220px-Mukesh_malayalam.jpg', 1, 'Mukesh (born Mukesh Babu on October 21, 1960) is an Indian film actor and producer known for his work in Malayalam cinema.', 0),
(58, 'Kalabhavan Mani', 'http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/KalabhavanManiMay2010.JPG/220px-KalabhavanManiMay2010.JPG', 1, 'Kalabhavan Mani (Malayalam: à´•à´²à´¾à´­à´µàµ» à´®à´£à´¿; born 1 January 1971) is a South Indian actor and singer. He began his career in Malayalam film industry, later he became a busy artist in Tamil and telugu industry, especially in villain roles. Although he began his career as a comedian, he proved his versatility in various roles such as serious actor, heroic and villain. He has acted in a number of films in Malayalam and Tamil. He has proved his acting talent in the movies called Vasantiyum Lakshmiyum Pinne Njanum, in which he plays a blind street singer.', 0),
(59, 'Rahman (actor)', 'http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/Actorrahman.JPG/200px-Actorrahman.JPG', 1, 'Rahman (born Rashin Rahman on 23 May 1967 in Abu Dhabi, Trucial States) is an Indian film actor who has acted in Malayalam, Tamil, and Telugu films. He made his debut in Koodevide (1983), and has appeared in more than 150 films, including Parannu Parannu Parannu (1984), Chilambu (1986), Pappan Priyappetta Pappan (1986), Pudhu Pudhu Arthangal (1989), and Nee Pathi Naan Pathi (1991).', 0),
(60, 'Anwar Rasheed', 'http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/f/f4/Ambox_content.png', 1, 'Anwar Rasheed is a Malayali Indian film director notable for his debut film Rajamanikyam (2005) starring Mammootty. His second feature film was Chotta Mumbai (2007), which had Mohanlal in the lead role. He reunited with Mammootty for his third feature Annan Thambi (2008).', 0),
